                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">The Linksys WRT54G wireless router has a lot of free firmware. One of the more popular ones are found <a href="http://forums.anandtech.com/messageview.aspx?catid=40&threadid=1343138&enterthread=y" target="_blank" class="postlink">here.</a> It's a link to another forum but it has a lot of info on it. 
<br />

<br />
The speed drop from using a router is imperceptible to the average user. I find using one computer as a gateway cumbersome since you must have the computer that's acting as a gateway on at all times you wish to use the secondary computer. A router splits the connection with no fuss and no muss. It also is ready should you ever add a 3rd or 4th computer to it. The prices for routers and ethernet cards have dropped so dramatically that it makes sense to use a router. All new computers come with ethernet and some motherboards like the one I have comes with two gigabit ethernet ports. Most home or small office routers only support 10/100. I have an 8 port gigabit switch for the home network which connects to my router which is where the DSL modem is connected to.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
