                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>ezzmirelda wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">If I used the gateway method wouldnt that bog down my main pc?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
It should not because routing packets is not particularly demanding.  This is not to say some software for PC routing can not perform very poorly but there is no particular reason it should bog down any system.
<br />

<br />
My m0n0wall router is running on a Packard Bell Pentium 60 with 40MBytes of RAM that I found in a closet at work.  Most consumer type routers you will find are not a whole lot more powerful then that and they can route at least 20MBits/sec.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>ezzmirelda wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">And how would it effect the internet speed of my second pc?</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
This would depend on the details of the software.  In general when using Windows ICS, Winroute, or Sygate I have never noticed any problems.  I do prefer dedicated routers just for the convenience and reliability.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Banished Soul Talc
