<br />
<a href="http://www.compusa.com/products/product_info.asp?product_code=310695&pfp=SEARCH" target="_blank" class="postlink">D-Link AirPlus G DWL-G630 Wireless Cardbus Adapter 802.11g</a> - Wireless network card for laptops. $19.99 after rebate.
<br />
<a href="http://www.compusa.com/products/product_info.asp?product_code=311434&pfp=BROWSE" target="_blank" class="postlink">6800G Plug&Share Wireless Router, 802.11g</a> - AT&T 802.11g router with integrated 4 port 10/100 Base-T switch (the ethernet ports basically). $19.99 with instant savings so no rebate needed.
<br />
<a href="http://www.compusa.com/products/product_info.asp?product_code=316644&pfp=BROWSE" target="_blank" class="postlink">6850G Plug&Share Wireless Router, 802.11g</a> - A better version of the above router. Has a few extra features and costs $10 more. $29.99 with instant savings.
<br />

<br />
For those who think getting a router and wireless cards are expensive. You just have to catch the right deals at the right time. I know a lot of you hate rebates but you do get the money back...eventually. And that ATT wireless router is a nice deal in that you don't even have to send in a rebate, it's an instant $30 off. CompUSA has penny shipping if you spend $150 and up.
<br />

<br />
Those products above are not free but they can be had relatively cheaply after rebates and other discounts are factored in. 
<br />

<br />
I really doubt you lose much bandwith from the overhead that is required by a router. After all, any modern 10/100 Base-T router/switch is way faster than any DSL service out there. And that's not even getting into the Gigabit switches like the one I use for my home network. That said, I would not get a wireless network for gaming. I'd get a router with switch capabilites like the AT&T ones I linked above and then use that for gaming. With the current state of wireless networking, an ethernet network will beat it hands down.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
