                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Vizier wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">I know this isnt answering your question but you really dont need a router with only 2 computers connecting to the internet. In fact routers assign bandwidth very inefficiently so unless you have like 4+ computers connecting through one ip address you should just set up your fastest computer as a gateway for the other computer. Gateways cost you zero dollars and take about 10 minutes to set up. Theres a ton of step by step tutorial in the How To section of <a href="http://www.pcworld.com" target="_blank">www.pcworld.com</a> . The other added benefit of a gateway is that it wont split your total bandwidth between 2 computers like a router does.
<br />

<br />
Just some friendly free advice from a computer guru. <img src="images/smiles/icon_smile.gif" alt="icon_smile.gif" border="0" /></td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Please don't do this. While this is true in a sense when you are talking about raw speed, this is a security problem. Even if you have one machine, the cable or DSL modem should be connected to the router, and not the PC, otherwise you lose the basic blocking functions of NAT.
<br />

<br />
See the various hits from:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.google.com/search?sourceid=navclient&ie=UTF-8&rls=GGLD,GGLD:2004-38,GGLD:en&q=NAT+router+security" target="_blank">http://www.google.com/search?sourceid=navclient&ie=UTF-8&rls=GGLD,GGLD:2004-38,GGLD:en&q=NAT+router+security</a>
<br />

<br />
This little guy is inexpensive and does the job:
<br />

<br />
<a href="http://www.netgear.com/products/details/FM114P.php" target="_blank">http://www.netgear.com/products/details/FM114P.php</a>
<br />

<br />
Good luck!</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
