                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody">What Talc said. My router doesn't have traffic shaping but I use Netlimiter 1.3 which does a similar job. The only downside is that it's another app constantly running that is hogging up resources. It can monitor individual programs and have it limit the upload and download limits on each or it can limit the total amount of upload or download bandwith for your computer as a whole. Very easy to set up. 
<br />

<br />
A router for the average Joe is just a better solution and the cost is really not that much if you're smart about buying it and catch it on a sale or rebate. All modern computers (within the last 5 years) should have an ethernet port either as an add-on card or built in. So you really only need a router and some ethernet cables. It's hassle free and very quick. There are also NAT and hardware firewall features that help to protect the user. Especially if you're going to be on a public P2P network.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br /><span style="font-style: italic">On the other hand, if your reaction to something I say boils down to "You didn't choose MY side, make MY choice," well, you're not looking for information, you're looking for someone to tell you how smart you are thinking the way you do. --</span> <span style="font-weight: bold">Ed Stroligo</span></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
