        <tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row2"><a name="99649"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Vizier</span></span><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_offline.gif" border="0" align="absbottom" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_7.gif" alt="<b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center>" title="<b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center>" border="0" /><br /><b><center><font color=red>Sage</font></b></center></div><div align="center"><img src="http://everquest.allakhazam.com/uf/Primist/ying.gif" alt="Avatar" border="0" /></div><br /><div align="left" class="gensmall">Joined:&nbsp;24 Sep 2003</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Total posts:&nbsp;551</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Location:&nbsp;Washington DC</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Male</div></td>
                <td class="row2" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=99649#99649"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 22, 2005 12:04 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=99649"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Badmorda wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A hub runs about $12-15...not sure what the point is. If you are going to connect more than two computers, you are going to want a hub anyway. Speaking of connecting multiple computers...why did you say a gateway is better for 4 or less computers? Why does a router become better for more than 4? Or, why is a gateway better for 4 or less computers? 
<br />
</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Hub or no hub you need 2 ethernet cards on the gateway computer. One card goes to the cable modem, the other card connects to the 2nd computer (or hub). The you simply bridge the connections.
<br />

<br />
The reason that a gateway is better for 4 or fewer computers has to do with the way routers assign bandwidth. For instance, if you have 2 computers sharing one ip address a router will divide the total bandwidth in half, giving each computer an equal share. That works ok in some situations but what if I am doing some online gaming or downloading while my wife is using her computer for Excell or something? In that case im only getting half my bandwidth while the other half is essentially wasted. A gateway eliminates that problem by giving each client the bandwith it requests on the fly.
<br />

<br />
A router's real advantage comes into play when you want to connect many (approx 3-4 or more) computers through 1 ip address. In that case your gateway computer may start to bog down a bit if all 4 computers are surfing at the same time, depending on how fast your system is of course. 
<br />

<br />
As to the so called "advantage" of having a built in firewall, personally I think this is simply another disadvantage. Example: I play some online games such as Age of Wonders and Warhammer 40k and Warcraft 3 that require other clients to connect directly to my computer. In some cases these games will NOT work with a firewall up. I use Windows XP's built in firewall and I can turn it on and off in about 15 seconds, no restart required even. Theres no such option with a router.
<br />

<br />
EDIT: One option that hasnt been discussed is simply getting another IP address from your cable company. Comcast charges a measly $4/month for a second IP. If that is in your price range you wouldnt need a gateway or a router and it would be faster than either one.</span><span class="postbody"></span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
                </table></td>
        </tr>
	<tr>
