        <tr>
		<td width="150" align="left" valign="top" class="row1"><a name="99698"></a><span class="name"><span class="usercolor">Talc</span></span><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_offline.gif" border="0" align="absbottom" alt="Offline" title="Offline" /><div class="gensmall"><img src="images/ranks/rank_1.gif" alt="Enchanter" title="Enchanter" border="0" /><br />Enchanter</div><div align="center"><img src="images/avatars/20675391083f4e450f90f79.jpg" alt="Avatar" border="0" /></div><br /><div align="left" class="gensmall">Joined:&nbsp;28 Aug 2003</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Total posts:&nbsp;31</div><div align="left" class="gensmall">Gender:&nbsp;Unknown</div></td>
                <td class="row1" width="100%" height="28" valign="top"><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
                        <tr>
                                <td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td><a href="viewtopic.php?p=99698#99698"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Tue Mar 22, 2005 9:10 pm<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: </span></td>
                                <td align="right" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap"><a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=99698"><img src="templates/subSilver/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>    </td></tr></table></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><hr /></td>
                        </tr>
                        <tr>
                                <td colspan="2"><span class="postbody"></span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Vizier wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">For instance, if you have 2 computers sharing one ip address a router will divide the total bandwidth in half, giving each computer an equal share.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unless your router supports traffic shaping and you have it set to specifically do this, it will not divide bandwidth.  When too many packets are queued for transmission, it will drop some and usually it will drop them in a random manner that is not particularly optimal.  If all packets come from one system, that system gets all the bandwidth available.
<br />

<br />
</span><table width="90%" cellspacing="1" cellpadding="3" border="0" align="center"><tr> 	  <td><span class="genmed"><b>Vizier wrote:</b></span></td>	</tr>	<tr>	  <td class="quote">A router's real advantage comes into play when you want to connect many (approx 3-4 or more) computers through 1 ip address. In that case your gateway computer may start to bog down a bit if all 4 computers are surfing at the same time, depending on how fast your system is of course.</td>	</tr></table><span class="postbody">
<br />

<br />
Unless something is very wrong with a home system that is being used as a gateway/router, you would be very hard pressed to overload it in any way.  Any computer someone would be using for EQ in the past 5 years should be able to easily saturate a few 100Mbit/s ethernet links when used as a router.</span><span class="postbody"><br />_________________<br />Banished Soul Talc
<br />

<br />
<span style="font-style: italic">He either fears his fate too much,
<br />
or his desserts are small
<br />
who dares not put it to the touch,
<br />
to win or lose it all.</span> - Montrose</span><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
                        </tr>
